sing metadata in version 2.5.0 requires editing existing tests rather than creating new ones. Overall, the issue relates to native-image run failures for tests with GVM_TCK_LV=2.5.0.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating library setup for tests**\\n\\nI need to figure out if the library requires any extra setup beyond the standard test scaffold to ensure meaningful coverage. For the issue related to fixes for the native image run, the driver might need to prepare a new version copy. The existing tests already have setup, but if there are missing dependencies, that could cause issues. I should look into the actual failure line after the native image run—possibly something about the cache being null.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining Ehcache 2.5 and dependencies**\\n\\nI’m trying to understand if Ehcache 2.5 requires a maximum byte size for the local heap. I'm thinking the Native Image run might fail if the AgentLoader tries to attach. If tests are using CacheConfiguration with eternal settings, does that trigger memory sizing issues? I should generate a dependency tree for ehcache-core, checking the provided POM. Since no SLF4J binding is needed, it’s good that the build lacks one. Finally, I should inspect 2.5.0 classes for default XML config resources.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Verifying POM for servlet dependencies**\\n\\nI think I need to verify the POM parent versions for the servlet because they might not specify everything clearly. It's important to assess relevant dependencies and perhaps include JTA under deterministic settings. I’ll need to check if the output action \\\"advisory_preparation\\\" provides any guidance. The deterministic setup could include javax.transaction:jta:1.1 with a testImplementation scope, since ehcache-core declares JTA as provided, and the transaction/XA APIs expose javax.transaction types.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Researching Java source and transactions**\\n\\nI need to find the Java source and possibly inspect class strings. Is using jar streaming a good approach? I’m thinking of downloading it to a cache directory, but that might modify something outside the repository. Maybe that's okay? I’m also considering using a URL jar, though that seems tricky. Also, I'm wondering if existing tests use Bitronix due to the Ehcache documentation. Time to look into transaction documentation for more insights!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_H4lZRSh9k2ORUpCWdO5EVGjS|fc_053957cfae486bd7016a4292c76b2c8197b55dcd00aea90f3f", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "python - <<'PY'\nimport urllib.request, re\nurls=['https://www.ehcache.org/documentation/2.8/apis/transactions.html','https://www.ehcache.org/documentation/2.7/apis/transactions.html','https://www.ehcache.org/documentation/2.5/apis/transactions.html','https://www.ehcache.org/documentation/2.8/apis.html']\nfor url in urls:\n    try:\n        req=urllib.request.Request(url, headers={'User-Agent':'Mozilla/5.0'})\n        text=urllib.request.urlopen(req, timeout=20).read().decode(errors='ignore')\n        print('\\nURL',url,'len',len(text))\n        for pat in ['Bitronix','javax.transaction','transactionalMode','DefaultTransactionManagerLookup','JTA','CacheManager']:\n            m=re.search(pat, text, re.I)\n            if m: print(' ',pat,'=>', re.sub(r'\\s+',' ',text[m.start()-160:m.start()+350])[:550])\n    except Exception as e: print('ERR', url, e)\nPY", "timeout": 60}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1136, "output": 1631, "cacheRead": 26624, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 29391, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1782747825758, "responseId": "resp_053957cfae486bd7016a4292b251f48197805127d7f711c02a"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_H4lZRSh9k2ORUpCWdO5EVGjS|fc_053957cfae486bd7016a4292c76b2c8197b55dcd00aea90f3f", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "\nURL https://www.ehcache.org/documentation/2.8/apis/transactions.html len 39937\n  Bitronix => the control of a Transaction Manager. This is typically provided by your application server, however you may also use a third party transaction manager such as Bitronix. To use Global Transactions, select either <code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">xa_strict</code> or <code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">xa</code> mode. The differences are explained in the sections below.</p> <h3 id=\"implementation\">Implementation</h3> <p>Global transactions support is implemented at the Store level, through XATransactionStore and\n  transactionalMode => n setting.</li> </ul> <h2 id=\"configuration\">Configuration</h2> <p>Transactions are enabled on a cache by cache basis with the <code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">transactionalMode</code> cache attribute. The allowed values are:</p> <ul> <li><code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">xa_strict</code></li> <li><code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">xa</code></li> <li><code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">local</code></li> <li><code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">off</code></li> </ul> <p>The default value is off. Enabling a cach\n  DefaultTransactionManagerLookup => ode class=\"highlighter-rouge\">net.sf.ehcache.transaction.manager.TransactionManagerLookup</code> and specify it in place of the <code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">DefaultTransactionManagerLookup</code> in <code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">ehcache.xml</code>:</p> <div class=\"highlighter-rouge\"> <div class=\"highlight\"> <pre class=\"highlight\"> <code>&lt;transactionManagerLookup class= \"com.mycompany.transaction.manager.MyTransactionManagerLookupClass\" properties=\"\" propertySeparator=\":\"/&gt\n  JTA => lighter-rouge\">xa</code> Use this mode when you cache data from other data stores (eg: DBMS, JMS) and want to do it in an atomic way under the control of the JTA API but don’t want to pay the price of full two-phase commit. In this mode, your cached data can get out of sync with the other resources participating in the transactions in case of a crash so only use it if you can afford to live with stale data for a brief period of time.</li> <li><code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">xa_strict</code> Same as \n  CacheManager => vlet shows a complete transaction.</p> <div class=\"highlighter-rouge\"> <div class=\"highlight\"> <pre class=\"highlight\"> <code>Ehcache cache = cacheManager.getEhcache(\"xaCache\"); UserTransaction ut = getUserTransaction(); printLine(servletResponse, \"Hello...\"); try { ut.begin(); int index = serviceWithinTx(servletResponse, cache); printLine(servletResponse, \"Bye #\" + index); ut.commit(); } catch(Exception e) { printLine(servletResponse, \"Caught a \" + e.getClass() + \"\n\nURL https://www.ehcache.org/documentation/2.7/apis/transactions.html len 39937\n  Bitronix => the control of a Transaction Manager. This is typically provided by your application server, however you may also use a third party transaction manager such as Bitronix. To use Global Transactions, select either <code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">xa_strict</code> or <code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">xa</code> mode. The differences are explained in the sections below.</p> <h3 id=\"implementation\">Implementation</h3> <p>Global transactions support is implemented at the Store level, through XATransactionStore and\n  transactionalMode => n setting.</li> </ul> <h2 id=\"configuration\">Configuration</h2> <p>Transactions are enabled on a cache by cache basis with the <code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">transactionalMode</code> cache attribute. The allowed values are:</p> <ul> <li><code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">xa_strict</code></li> <li><code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">xa</code></li> <li><code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">local</code></li> <li><code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">off</code></li> </ul> <p>The default value is off. Enabling a cach\n  DefaultTransactionManagerLookup => ode class=\"highlighter-rouge\">net.sf.ehcache.transaction.manager.TransactionManagerLookup</code> and specify it in place of the <code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">DefaultTransactionManagerLookup</code> in <code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">ehcache.xml</code>:</p> <div class=\"highlighter-rouge\"> <div class=\"highlight\"> <pre class=\"highlight\"> <code>&lt;transactionManagerLookup class= \"com.mycompany.transaction.manager.MyTransactionManagerLookupClass\" properties=\"\" propertySeparator=\":\"/&gt\n  JTA => lighter-rouge\">xa</code> Use this mode when you cache data from other data stores (eg: DBMS, JMS) and want to do it in an atomic way under the control of the JTA API but don’t want to pay the price of full two-phase commit. In this mode, your cached data can get out of sync with the other resources participating in the transactions in case of a crash so only use it if you can afford to live with stale data for a brief period of time.</li> <li><code class=\"highlighter-rouge\">xa_strict</code> Same as \n  CacheManager => vlet shows a complete transaction.</p> <div class=\"highlighter-rouge\"> <div class=\"highlight\"> <pre class=\"highlight\"> <code>Ehcache cache = cacheManager.getEhcache(\"xaCache\"); UserTransaction ut = getUserTransaction(); printLine(servletResponse, \"Hello...\"); try { ut.begin(); int index = serviceWithinTx(servletResponse, cache); printLine(servletResponse, \"Bye #\" + index); ut.commit(); } catch(Exception e) { printLine(servletResponse, \"Caught a \" + e.getClass() + \"\nERR https://www.ehcache.org/documentation/2.5/apis/transactions.html HTTP Error 404: Not Found\nERR https://www.ehcache.org/documentation/2.8/apis.html HTTP Error 404: Not Found\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1782747849397}]}
